#a) Load the Iris dataset and examine its structure.

from sklearn import datasets

irisDS = iris.data
df = pd.DataFrame(data=irisDS, columns=iris.feature_names)
print(df)
print(df.mean())
print(df.min())
print(df.max())

#(c) Split the dataset into training (80%) and testing sets (20%).
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(irisDS, iris.target, test_size=0.2)
#Test_size = 0.2 = 20% Data set

#Resulting sets
print("shape of original dataset: ", irisDS.shape)
print("shape of input - training set", x_train.shape)
print("shape of output - training set", y_train.shape)
print("shape of input - testing set", x_test.shape)
print("shape of output - testing set", y_test.shape)

shape of original dataset:  (150, 4)
shape of input - training set (120, 4)

shape of input - testing set (30, 4)
shape of output - testing set (30,)

(c)

There's 150 rows in this dataset. 1.5 = 1%, 15 = 10%, 30 = 20%.

This was split up into 80%/20% splits. That's why the train.shape's are 120 & the test.shape's are 30.

It's common pracctice for the split to be 80/20, and that is done by doing test_size = 0.2 when Splitting the Dataset.

#(a) Implement a decision tree classifier using scikit-learn's DecisionTreeClassifier class.
#(b) Train the decision tree classifier on the training data.
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

#Decision Tree
classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=2)
classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)

Accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, classifier.predict(x_test))
print("Accuracy:", Accuracy)
print(classification_report(y_test, classifier.predict(x_test)))

This is done using classifier.fit(). we can use .prediction to make predictions on the testing set. Following this, the model is evaluated. It's calculated by using the accuracy_score function. (b) This code creates a decision tree classifier. The state is random using 'random_state=2' for reproducability. And then it trains the classifier using training data.

The 'random_state' parameter in the 'DecisionTreeClassifier' constructor is used for RNG. Because the random state is fixed at 2, it means it is reproducible.

In [ ]:
#(c) Set and tune hyperparameters like the maximum depth of the tree,
#minimum samples per leaf, or other relevant parameters.
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Hyperparameters
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [None, 1, 5, 10],  # Maximum depth of the decision tree. None = unrestricted depth.
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 5, 10]  # Minimum samples per leaf as 1 2, 5, or 10.
}
grid_search = GridSearchCV(classifier, param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_) #I swear these _'s annoy me

# Most suitable Hyperparameters
best_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=2,
    max_depth=grid_search.best_params_['max_depth'],
    min_samples_leaf=grid_search.best_params_['min_samples_leaf'])
best_classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)


# Evaluate the model with the best hyperparameters
accuracy_best = accuracy_score(y_test, best_classifier.predict(x_test))
print("Accuracy with best hyperparameters:", accuracy_best)
print(classification_report(y_test, best_classifier.predict(x_test)))

Best Parameters: {'max_depth': None, 'min_samples_leaf': 2}

(c) Set and tune hyperparameters like the maximum depth of the tree, minimum samples per leaf, or other relevant parameters.

The max depth controls the depth of the DT. The Maximum depth being none mean there is no restriction on how deep it should go. The min_samples_leaf controls the minimum number of samples required to be at the node. So we have them as either 1,2,5, or 10.

GridSearchCV searches through param_grid using Cross-Validation It then shows the best combinations found by the grid to get the highest performance.

We go on to get the most suitable hyperparamaeters, predict the testing set and show that the end result is.

As you can see, it worked. because it shows it is 1.00 accurate.
